            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe remembers being eight, kneeling in his mother\u2019s Richmond District shop. The air smelled of wool and tea. She had him close his eyes and feel the density of a Tabriz rug\u2019s knots. \u201cValue is a story you feel, Kian-jan,\u201d she\u2019d said. It was the first time he understood that quality wasn\u2019t a price tag, but a tangible history. This sensory lesson became the foundation of his uncanny ability to discern future bestsellers from mere products, a silent language passed from mother to son.\n\n2.\nAt 24, he was an assistant buyer at a chaotic Las Vegas trade show. While senior buyers buzzed around sequins and loud prints, Kian found himself drawn to a small booth with simple, unadorned cashmere-blend scarves. He felt that familiar hum of quality, the echo of his mother\u2019s lesson. He staked his reputation on a massive order. His boss called it a risk. Six months later, it was the company\u2019s top-selling accessory. It was the moment his quiet confidence found its voice in the corporate world.\n\n3.\nHe was 35, standing in a starkly modern hotel room in Milan. It was his wedding anniversary. His wife\u2019s voice on the phone was tired, not angry, as she described her dinner alone. Looking at his perfectly pressed suit for the next day's meetings, he felt the sharp pang of a poorly executed trade-off. He had curated a successful career but had let his own life become a casualty. That quiet, transatlantic call was the moment he understood the true, non-negotiable cost of his ambition.\n\n4.\nLast year, on his MUNI ride home, the train surfaced from the tunnel into the Castro. He saw the reflection of his own tailored suit superimposed over the vibrant, evolving streetscape. He felt a sudden, sharp disconnect. His parents had built something tangible in the Richmond, a part of the city's fabric. He, in his Financial District tower, merely managed things. That 2.1-mile commute, once a symbol of efficiency, suddenly felt like a journey between two selves: the man he was and the man he should be.\n\n5.\nTwo months ago, at a weekly dinner, his father spoke of a young jewelry maker struggling with retailers. Without thinking, Kian outlined a three-point strategy for her: how to position her brand, approach buyers, and scale production. He saw a light in his parents\u2019 eyes he hadn\u2019t seen in years\u2014pride not just in his success, but in his knowledge. In that moment, his future clicked into place. It wouldn't be about climbing higher, but about building a bridge back, using his corporate expertise to champion a new generation of artisans."
